Angola: Marburg death toll rising; 2nd northern province involved
-----------------------------------------------
Another young woman has died of Marburg virus infection in Angola,
officials said, as the death toll in the deadly outbreak rose to almost
equal the most serious outbreak ever recorded. Some 121 people have died
since the hemorrhagic fever virus first broke out in the northern town
[province] of Uige in October 2004, while 5 more people, including a
Portuguese citizen, have been hospitalized, bringing the toll of sick to
132. Until now, the most serious recorded outbreak of the disease was in
the Democratic Republic of Congo between 1998 and 2000, when 123 people died.
A South African travel clinic on Sunday [27 Mar 2005] warned travelers
planning to go to Angola to stay away from the country "for at least a
week," quoting reports that residents of the capital Luanda, especially
expatriates, were contemplating evacuating the country.
The young woman died on Sunday [27 Mar 2005] at a hospital in Uige some 300
km (180 miles) north of Luanda, and 3 people with the disease, including
one child, were admitted there, while in Luanda, a 12-year-old girl and a
Portuguese national were hospitalized.
Luanda provincial health director Vita Mvemba said in the capital: "One
Portuguese citizen who has visited Uige was admitted on Sunday [27 Mar
2005] at the military hospital, and one girl, about 12 years old, has been
transferred from the Cacuaco Health Centre to the Americo Boa Vida
hospital." Cacuaco is a suburb about 6 km (4 miles) north of Luanda on the
road to Uige. "The girl is from Luanda. She has been admitted with a fever
for the last 2 days at the Cacuaco Centre. Today [Sun 27 Mar 2005], she
started bleeding. That's why we urgently had to transfer her to the Americo
Boa Vida hospital," Mvemba said.
Alberto added: "3 Chinese experts in epidemiology have gone to join medical
teams in Uige in the battle against the Marburg virus."
