Angola: Marburg hemorrhagic fever death toll continues to rise
-----------------------------------------------
Health officials in Luanda are worried that 3 patients who died of the
Marburg [hemorrhagic fever] maybe have come into contact with more people
in Luanda. The death toll from the disease in Angola rose to 112 on Friday
[25 Mar 2005], with 3 deaths reported in Lusaka for the 1st time. "We are
running tests on family members and people they might have been in contact
with to rule out infection of others," health official Vita Vemba told
Lusa. A 15-year-old boy, an Italian aid worker and a Vietnamese doctor had
died in Luanda, health officials said, according to the Portuguese news
agency Lusa. 2 other cases of the Marburg illness were detected in Luanda.
All 5 patients had come from Uige, the province along the Congo border
where the outbreak was 1st reported.
"Marburg virus disease occurs very rarely and appears to be geographically
confined to a small number of countries in the southern part of the African
continent," WHO has said. "When cases do occur, the disease has epidemic
potential, as it can spread from person to person, most often during the
care of patients." Previous outbreaks have indicated that the risk of
infection is increased by close contact with bodily fluids of infected
people, which may occur during treatment or burial practices, WHO said.
About 3/4ths of cases have occurred in children under 5, and a small number
of health care workers are among those adults infected, WHO said on Tuesday
[22 Mar 2005].
