Source: The Standard online, Mon 28 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.eastandard.net/hm_news/news.php?articleid=16517>

Kenya: help sought to stop Marburg epidemic
-----------------------------------------------
Kenya has sought the help of the World Health Organization to stop the
deadly Marburg virus from spreading into the country. The virus has killed
120 people in Angola. The Director of Medical Services, Dr. James Nyikal,
said WHO will give advice on surveillance measures later this week [final
week March 2005]. Kenya is particularly concerned, because it is among the
few countries in which [Marburg] virus has struck twice before; in 1980 and
1987. It killed 2 people on both occasions, but was swiftly contained
before it could spread further.
Dr. Nyikal said that: "We have talked to WHO to advise us on what to do. We
do not take chances whenever an outbreak is reported in the region." Kenya
took the action soon after 21 Mar 2005, when laboratory tests confirmed
several people who have died in Angola since November last year [2004] were
infected with the virus.
Medical experts and WHO say it is transmitted through close contact with
infected patients and body fluids. In the 1st cases of infection, relatives
and friends of infected patients become victims, as it initially displays
symptoms similar to those of malaria, typhoid and other common diseases.
Homes of infected persons soon become centers of death, as anyone coming to
contact falls ill and dies. Patients experience agonizing severe diarrhea,
abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, severe chest and lung pains, sore throat
and cough. It later progresses into severe bleeding and death. Marburg
spreads fast and is easily spread to doctors and family members caring for
infected loved ones. "When cases occur, the disease has epidemic potential,
as it can spread from person to person, most often during the care of
patients," WHO said in a statement last Wednesday [23 Mar 2005].
WHO names Kenya among the few countries in sub-Saharan Africa where the
disease appears to be geographically contained. Cases have occurred in
Angola, the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Uganda and South Africa.
However, the virus was first identified in Germany and Yugoslavia, where it
had traveled with green monkeys imported from Uganda. It attacks
sporadically, killing its victims and disappearing for years before
resurfacing. However, despite intensive investigations over the years,
research has failed to find an animal reservoir of the virus or to
determine where it hides in nature between outbreaks.
Yesterday [Sun 27 Mar 2005], the director of the Kenya Medical Research
Institute, Dr. Davy Koech, said the institute was closely monitoring events
in Angola and assessing the need for a response here. He said there was no
need yet to screen visitors in Kenya's airports and border posts, but added
it would be easy for even untrained people to suspect a case if one landed
in the airports. "Because there are no direct flights from Angola to Kenya,
it is unlikely that a traveler would land in the airport without advanced
symptoms. The disease would have shown up in the time people spend
connecting flights," Dr. Koech said.
In the 1st case in Kenya in 1980, one person was infected in the Mt. Elgon
area, not far from the Uganda region where the monkeys had been trapped. He
spread the virus to his attending physician, who survived. The virus
disappeared, only to emerge again in Kenya in 1987. The infected man died.
It was suspected that the man infected in 1980 may have contracted the
virus in a cave where he had visited. But when medical researchers put
animals in the cave, no virus was traced, and the animals remained healthy.
The virus was first identified in 1967, when simultaneous outbreaks were
reported among laboratory workers in Marburg and Frankfurt, Germany and in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia. 7 people died in the outbreak, in which 31 people
were infected. Investigations revealed the victims had come into contact
with monkeys imported from Uganda. It disappeared for 8 years, reappearing
with an infection of a man in South Africa who had recently traveled from
Zimbabwe. The man infected his traveling companion and a nurse. While the 2
survived, the man died. The largest recorded outbreak, according to WHO,
occurred between 1998 and 2000 in the DRC, where it killed 123 people out
of 149 infected.
WHO recommends that containment of an outbreak of Marburg virus disease
requires rapid tracing and isolation of contacts. People living near
outbreak zones are educated on ways to avoid infection, and communities are
informed of the risks associated with traditional burial practices.
[Byline: Patrick Mathangani]
