Source: Macleans.com, News, Canadian Press, Sat 26 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.macleans.ca/topstories/politics/news/shownews.jsp?content=n032619A>

Angola: Canada sends unique mobile laboratory
-----------------------------------------------
Canada is sending a one-of-a-kind portable laboratory to Angola to help
contain [the Marburg hemorrhagic] fever outbreak that has killed more than
100 people since October 2004. Dr. Heinz Feldman, an expert in deadly
pathogens, is set to arrive in the southwestern African country on Tue 29
Mar 2005 as part of a global response to halt the spread of Marburg fever,
a viral disease with no cure or vaccine that doctors have said can be
"rapidly fatal."
Feldman and Allen Grolla, a laboratory technician, will be able to quickly
diagnose cases of Marburg virus infection, which health officials on the
ground have been unable to do. So far, only 5 cases have been confirmed,
but at least 112 people have died from the virus, according to Angolan
officials. Dr. Frank Plummer, scientific director of Canada's National
Microbiology Laboratory in Winnipeg, said on-site testing is critical,
because early symptoms, such as fevers and headaches, are vague and not
necessarily telltale signs of the disease. "It's very important in the
middle of this kind of an epidemic to be able to make a diagnosis quickly,
because there's lots of different causes of fever," Plummer said.
Health experts are acutely concerned about this outbreak for several
reasons. About 3/4ths of those infected are children under 5, and its scope
is unusually large; the majority of other outbreaks have involved one or 2
cases. It can also take a long time to curb the spread of the virus, which
has a mortality rate of more than 90 percent. The last outbreak of Marburg,
in the Democratic Republic of Congo, took 2 years to control, said Dick
Thompson, spokesman for the World Health Organization.
Unease grew last week [4th week March 2005], after Marburg was detected in
the Angolan capital of Luanda, a city of nearly 3 million. Medical experts
fear hospital staff may have been inadvertently exposed, further
transmitting the virus. In response, the WHO is sending a team of
laboratory experts, epidemiologists and infection-control specialists under
the auspices of the Global Outbreak Alert and Response Network.
Canada's mobile lab has been used to test cases of Ebola [hemorrhagic
fever] in Congo and the global transmission of SARS at Hong Kong's
Metropole Hotel. "If SARS taught us in the past, and as we're worrying now
with avian influenza, we live in a global environment, and these bugs
really know no bounds," Thompson said.
The Public Health Agency of Canada has issued a travel advisory since the
outbreak. It was first noticed along Angola's border with Congo, in Uige
province. Authorities initially feared the deaths were caused by Ebola,
which still exists in nature in Congo. Previous outbreaks have indicated
that the risk of infection is increased by close contact with bodily fluids
of infected people, as may occur during treatment or burial practices, WHO
said. It has an incubation period of 3 to 7 days. Between 1998 and late
2000, Congo recorded the largest outbreak of Marburg virus on record, when
149 cases were reported, with 123 deaths.
[Byline: Tara Brautigam]
